my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: Really high 3, practically a 4! Really interesting study on a relationship that jumps around in the timeline to slowly reveal how it developed, why thReally high 3, practically a 4! Really interesting study on a relationship that jumps around in the timeline to slowly reveal how it developed, why they have the issues they have with each other, and why they are the way they are. It’s not a romcom—more intellectual, with a lot of tangents that go into psychology and emotion and brain chemistry. Sometimes I loved these rants and sometimes they went a little too far—cut them by 30 percent and the book is a 4. But at the same time, these were why I loved the book so much—it made me reflect on my own daily motives and decision making and feelings. One particular speech that happens near the Bean in Chicago toward the end of the book will stick with me forever. Love a book that is entertaining but bleeds into my life in these kinds of ways and changes my thinking. It’s a long book to commit to, and definitely not for everyone because of the deep dives, but I really enjoyed it. ...more

review: I loved this book, which read like Hunger Games meets Just Mercy—dystopian action but as a major commentary on the modern prison system. It is satire,I loved this book, which read like Hunger Games meets Just Mercy—dystopian action but as a major commentary on the modern prison system. It is satire, and sometimes while you are reading and turning pages you start to think that you are so much like the audience in the book, disconnected and intrigued, or at worst taking this in as entertainment like you shouldn’t be. Loved the strong women presented in the book, and the humanity of every character, and the ways their humanity is jeopardized by the system they are in. It feels very vivid and possible and page turning, like a movie. And is so thought provoking as a call to action how we aren’t doing enough about the insanity of mass incarceration that is a part of our reality—as evidenced by several nonfiction footnotes in the book. Warning it is super violent. But it is so different from anything else I’ve read and I’m highly recommending. ...more

title: The Stand
author: King, Stephen*
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: I love this book in high school! Now I grew up and decided to give it the hold up test. The book is the same but I am different. :) Very cheesy, too mI love this book in high school! Now I grew up and decided to give it the hold up test. The book is the same but I am different. :) Very cheesy, too many words, and worst of all and the reason I had to abandon ship halfway through this time—it’s so racist. The skin of every non-white person is mentioned, and the only time a white person’s is mentioned it is described as olive. I thought, there you go, finally balancing out the need for a description. Then the olive skinned person started talking and had the thickest Italian accent. It’s like King lives in a world where white is a given and everyone else needs to be called out for not being normal. He uses and overuses the N word to get a point across about racist treatment. He describes the Asian person’s eyes every time he makes an appearance. It was truly ick and maddening. This was what made me stop. But I would have stopped anyway because it was predictable, good marching toward evil, and meant to be exciting but because of everything being so extreme was just boring. I think we need a redo of all the ratings for this book so far. It is from its time, and we can fault it for that as we reckon with the realities of systemic racism. ...more

review: Loved this eye-opening story about the crisis in Syria, told through the eyes of a girl on the cusp of adulthood. The characters come to life in a wayLoved this eye-opening story about the crisis in Syria, told through the eyes of a girl on the cusp of adulthood. The characters come to life in a way that makes you root for them and understand the impossible things they are living through and choices they have to make. You feel the everyday terrors, but you live them day by day with the characters as they go to their workplace and live out each moment—so it all feels visceral and real as you read it. You come to understand their love and hope for their country and what it is like to flee while still attached to a life you had planned. There’s also a love story and plenty of action to keep things moving. My favorite moment that got me was when everyone was singing together at a moment toward the end. I did struggle with the presence of one character—it will be obvious when you read it who I mean. At first I was sure he would be way too distracting, but it did get toned down enough and explained in a way that made me fine with him and understand the author’s choice by the end. review: I love David Sedaris and his weird brand of humor so much. I haven’t laughed out loud at a book in so long, and he got me with this one multiple timesI love David Sedaris and his weird brand of humor so much. I haven’t laughed out loud at a book in so long, and he got me with this one multiple times. He shines a spotlight on life in a pandemic state in a way that makes everyone feel just a little less crazy, surrounded by crazies. It fails to distinguish between assisted suicide for physical or other illness and suicide for reasons that should be considered temporary and overcome-able with support—grief, emotional hurt and pain, loneliness, guilt. In the wrong hands, this book will pull a lot of triggers and lead to a lot of loss. review: This was good but also highly overrated…I am shocked that so many people love this so much. I liked Ryle and Atlas, and I love a good love triangle. IThis was good but also highly overrated…I am shocked that so many people love this so much. I liked Ryle and Atlas, and I love a good love triangle. I just hated how much Ryle had to be taken down for this story. It would have been better as a sweet complicated romance without making it an issue story. I did not at all get empathy they tried building for Ryle. It felt like a false attempt to understand domestic abuse, giving Ryle a sympathetic backstory for why he was the way he was—a perfect guy except for this one crazy unfortunate thing that happened when he was a kid. When he snapped and wasn’t himself, that was his abuse?? It felt WAYYY too simplified compared to what real life domestic abuse chains must be. I didn’t understand at all why Lily kept staying with him, which was the opposite of what the author intended. And my overall impression of Atlas was..grossness, recovered? A good book that tried to do too much. ...more

review: Author-read audio essaysI enjoy John Green, although his fiction can get a little melodramatic and angsty for me. This collection of essays was good aAuthor-read audio essaysI enjoy John Green, although his fiction can get a little melodramatic and angsty for me. This collection of essays was good and full of fun science-y facts and earth-friendly pleas. The structure was cute-sy and gave the essays a bite-sized feel. However, I feel like that was the book’s demise—so many topics that he repeated and barely scraped the surface of a larger point before wrapping them up tidily and giving his 5-star scale rating. I found myself editing the book, which is never a good thing. For example, what if he combined the goose and Kentucky blue grass chapters and let the reader do some work on the deeper meanings and connections presented by these related topics?? I feel like anytime he found himself repeating some factoid, alarm bells should have went off to say, maybe this is the same story and can be used to build a point??? There were so many opportunities to combine and grow and it felt very new-to-writing-essays. Also, he read it himself and I noticed both he and Ann Patchett take very strange pauses… in their sentences… when reading their work out loud…distracting. I give this collection… of author-read essays…: 3 stars....more

author: Rooney, Sally*
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: Really loved this book. I feel like Sally Rooney wrote herself into Alice, which totally brought the character to life. Everyone else was so real. I lReally loved this book. I feel like Sally Rooney wrote herself into Alice, which totally brought the character to life. Everyone else was so real. I loved how the main parts of the novel were told through action with no inner dialogue, so you had to just apply meaning like a guess to what characters were doing and why—like in life. And then the emails gave you the inner monologue to show how characters actually felt about the conversations they had and what happened to them. Then you can see why relationships are so difficult to navigate—because, even if someone is your closest and best person in the world—you still don’t know at all what life is like for them. This simple but complex book was the best demonstration of how it feels to be human and alone and human and connected all at once. So good.Ps, 4 not 5 only because I can see how it would be slow for some people, or too philosophical in parts. But it was the right kind of book for me right now. ...more

I felt lost following all the characters, and I wanted the clues that were given to mean more and be more distinctive. I didn't really understand Westing's point in creating the game, I didn't understand who was the bomber and why, I didn't understand the timing and pacing of events—it felt like just a random time where some people were trying to uncover clues that didn't mean that much and suddenly it was over. I didn't feel satisfied with the final reveals at all. However, my kids loved it? So maybe it's best enjoyed without putting any expectations into it, or any hopes to discover the mystery yourself....more

A whodunnit where you suspect a bunch of people and then it was one of them. Nothing extraordinary here. I wanted more of a twist or a piling together of various clues or anything to excite or surprise me. I wanted more backstory on the kids’ growing animosity. I wanted there to actually be teamwork, or one murderer and a surprise second murderer. I wanted less clues that were immediately dismissed or explained. It lost a lot of suspense by giving itself away immediately. And I didn’t really understand at all why the sudden snap and quick double murder planning. Very boring that the only explanation is that she didn’t want to lose her inheritance…especially since the inheritance was still significant even if it was cut in half. Most boring double murder ever. I gave it a 3 and not a 2 because it was a fast read and a good palate cleanser between weightier books. ...more
